                                <div class=3D"post-hatom-fix">
								<span class=3D"entry-title">How to save power consumption in an RFI=
D reader?</span>
								<div class=3D"post-meta">by <a class=3D"vcard author" href=3D"https=
://iotlab.tertiumcloud.com/author/p-consani/" title=3D"View all posts by p.=
consani" itemprop=3D"author"><span class=3D"fn" itemprop=3D"name">p.consani=
</span></a>  </div>
							</div>                                <div class=3D"real-content ent=
ry-content" itemprop=3D"text">
                                    <p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Radio=
 Frequency Identification (RFID) technology is more widely used.<span id=3D=
"more-3117"></span></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">In particular, UHF RFID technology is att=
racting more and more because of its advantages including reading and write=
 distance. Power amplifiers occupy the majority of energy consumption in th=
e power consumption of UHF readers. In most applications, <span style=3D"co=
lor: #ff9900;">to maximize the read distance, transmit power is usually set=
 to a maximum which results in a waste of energy</span>.</p>
<p id=3D"tw-target-text" class=3D"tw-data-text tw-text-large XcVN5d tw-ta" =
dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;" data-placeholder=3D"Traduzione">=
<span lang=3D"en">To maximize the battery life of an RFID reader it is, the=
refore, necessary to save energy</span>. But how can you do it?</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Below, taking into consideration the <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.tertiumtechnology.com/en/products/uhf-mobile-reader/">Bl=
ueBerry HS UHF</a> portable passive reader, we will analyze two different a=
pproaches that will allow you to decrease power consumption, thus preservin=
g the device=E2=80=99s battery. In particular,</p>
<ol style=3D"text-align: justify;">
<li><span style=3D"color: #ff9900;">Decrease the RF power level in which th=
e reader is operating;</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: #ff9900;">Use the RF-off time parameter inside th=
e firmware in order to apply the duty cycle functionality</span>.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">These two approaches can be used simultan=
eously. Now, let=E2=80=99s start analyzing them one by one!!!</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span style=3D"color: #000080;">Decrease=
 the RF power level</span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">First of all, what is the<span style=3D"c=
olor: #333333;"> RF power level</span>? It is the amount of RF energy emitt=
ed from an RFID tag reader. The higher the power output the longer the read=
 range. So when you want to maximize the read range, you have to know that =
the reader consumes a large amount of power because it is operating at full=
 RF power. Accordingly, setting the <span style=3D"color: #ff9900;">RF powe=
r down</span>, it=E2=80=99s an easy way to reduce power consumption. Obviou=
sly, don=E2=80=99t forget that the decrease of the RF power level will be a=
t the expense of the <span style=3D"color: #ff9900;">reading range</span> w=
hich <span style=3D"color: #ff9900;">will shorten</span>!</p>
<p class=3D"tw-data-text tw-text-large XcVN5d tw-ta" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"t=
ext-align: justify;" data-placeholder=3D"Traduzione"><span lang=3D"en">Howe=
ver, the decrease of the two parameters is not linear. That is, if you halv=
e the RF power level, energy consumption decreases not by half, but by a mu=
ch smaller amount. The decrease is therefore not efficient</span>. This is =
because the RF power amplifiers (PAs) depends on many factors and above all=
 must be adapted to the output power loads. <span lang=3D"en">The efficienc=
y of PAs varies directly with the output power levels</span>, so if the eff=
iciency drops drastically as the output power level is reduced.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span style=3D"color: #000080;">Use an R=
F off time parameter in continue scanning mode</span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">To conserve power consumption in continue=
 scanning mode, it is possible to turn off the RF power amplifier for a sel=
ected time interval. Taking into consideration BlueBerry HS UHF, a practica=
l example is to <span style=3D"color: #ff9900;">avoid duty cycles</span> gr=
eater than 0.5 (600ms ON, 400ms OFF), but to prefer periods configured as 2=
00ms ON and 800ms OFF. So, the longer the RF off range is extended, the mor=
e power consumption saved, on the other hand the reader will have <span sty=
le=3D"color: #ff9900;">less reactive reading ability</span>. Unlike the app=
roach previously discussed, this will not affect the reading distance</p>
<p>In conclusion, to resume:</p>
